{"altmetric_id":13688004,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":36,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":25},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":24,"unique_users":["annaliisalaine","LouiseJJohnson","animalculum","kaylacking","C_Blei","danjbecker","LaPepena","wheatpath","HRPrendeville","amybpedersen","danielcroll","jaytlennon","alexander_suh","miguelacevedopr","BrockhurstLab","gottdenk","LigoxygakisLab","PaulineDScanlan","aquabolina","edzewestra","DanMorley86","viraleco_papers","Popgen_Papers","adsoconga1988"],"posts_count":25}},"selected_quotes":["Host diversity limits evolution of parasite local adaptation Special issue on Microbial Local A\u2026","@UniofExeter My first paper at","Testing predictions of local adaptation in a host-parasite system, first spotted","Host diversity limits evolution of parasite local adaptation Special issue on Microbial Local Adaptation in MolEcol"],"citation":{"abstract":"Specificity in the interactions between hosts and their parasites can lead to local adaptation. However, the degree of local adaptation is predicted to depend upon the diversity of resistance alleles within the host population; increasing host diversity should decrease mean parasite infectivity and hence reduce local adaptation. In this study we empirically test this prediction using the highly specific interactions between bacteria with CRISPR-Cas immunity and their bacteriophage. Bacteria acquire immunity to phage by incorporating a phage-derived spacer sequence into CRISPR loci on the host genome, and phage can escape the CRISPR-mediated immunity of a specific clone by mutating the targeted sequence. We found that high levels of CRISPR allele diversity which naturally evolve in host populations exposed to phage (because each bacterial clone captures a unique phage-derived sequence) prevents phage from becoming locally adapted. By manipulating the number of CRISPR alleles in the host population we show that phage can become locally adapted to their bacterial hosts